We have a fairly complicated project tree and we'd like to be able to require things with browserify relative to the cwd. So instead of writing `require('../../../../../app/out/models/mockup.js')` which is prone to change, we can write `require('app/out/models/mockup.js')` instead which is far less prone to change.

Another way to do this (which could be preferable) is:

``` javascript
// in our code
module.paths.push(process.cwd());
// in browserify
parent.paths = parent.paths.concat(module.paths);
```

or via an option.

It seems something like this is intended with https://github.com/balupton/node-browserify/blob/7ae499aa71f23d146af9d2dbd4e2f41403c9e218/index.js#L50 but I may be wrong about that.

This method allows you to add an alias to an external library, such as CDN-hosted jQuery:

```
b.link('jquery', 'window.jQuery');
browserify entry.js --link jquery:window.jQuery > bundle.js
```

In a module:

```
var $ = require('jquery');
$(function() { ... });
```

This lets other browserify modules rebuild the bundle (if desired), which is helpful when creating with web workers (specifically, it enables the following kind of module):

``` javascript
var worker = require('browserify-worker')

var thread = worker(function() {
  var EE = require('events').EventEmitter

  onmessage = function(ev) {
    postMessage('hello!') 
  }
}, __dirname)

thread.onmessage = function(ev) {
  console.log('got', ev)
}

thread.postMessage('you there?')
```

First, `browserify` is awsome.

I'm using it to bundle code for use inside a sandbox environment. As such, some of the `require`'d modules are provided by the environment.

When I have code like:
`index.js`

``` javascript
var fromBrowserify = require( './myFile.js' ),
    fromSandbox = require( 'magic-sandbox-string' );

// do stuff...
```

I would like to be able to `require.define( 'magic-sandbox-string', function (...` before the code above is bundled.

`bundle.prepend()` doesn't do this.
`bundle.append("require.define('magic-sandbox-string, function(/*...*/){});")` attaches the `require.define(..` code, but it does so only after generating above code, like this:

``` javascript
// ...
require.define("/index.js", function( /* ... */ ) {
// ...
});
require("/index.js");

require.define( 'magic-sandbox-string', function(/*...*/){} );
})();
```

What `bundle.insert("require.define('magic-sandbox-string, function(/*...*/){});")` does, is place the code where it can be used before final `require("/index.js");`, like so:

``` javascript
// ...
require.define( 'magic-sandbox-string', function(/*...*/){} );
require.define("/index.js", function( /* ... */ ) {
// ...
});
require("/index.js");
})();
```

I'm happy to write tests if you could give me a pointer as to where. I couldn't locate tests for `append` and `prepend`.

Cheers!

